---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "When is the best time to trap gophers?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Spring (February–May) is peak season — gophers are breeding hard and expanding territory fast. Fall (September–November) is the second major activity window as they cache food for winter. Hit both surges hard and you can stay ahead of the problem." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Are gophers active year-round?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "In Southern California, yes — gophers never fully stop. They slow down in winter and go deeper in summer heat, but activity continues throughout the year. In colder climates they reduce significantly in winter but do not hibernate." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Why do I see so many gopher mounds in spring?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Spring is peak breeding season. A single female can produce 2–3 litters of 5–6 pups between February and May. New tunnels go in fast and mounds can multiply overnight during this window — which is exactly why it's the most important time to be trapping." } },
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "When is the best time to install gopher mesh or barriers?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Winter (December–January) is ideal — gopher activity is at its lowest and you can get infrastructure in place before the spring breeding surge begins in February. Two hours of mesh installation in January is worth ten hours of emergency trapping in March." } },
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="Seasonal Gopher Activity Guide (2026) | Mark The Bagger"
  description="Know exactly when gophers are most active and what to do about it. Mark the Bagger's season-by-season field guide for gopher control in Southern California."
  schemas={[faqSchema]}
>
  <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <a href="/">Home</a> › Seasonal Guide
  </nav>

  <header class="calendar-hero">
    <h1>Gophers Don't Take Seasons Off. But They Have Patterns.</h1>
    <p class="cal-sub">Know when they surge, when they go deep, and when to hit hard.</p>
    <p class="cal-dateline">Updated March 2026</p>
    <ul class="season-strip" aria-label="Season overview">
      <li class="season-chip"><span class="s-icon">🌸</span><span class="s-name">Spring</span><span class="s-note">Peak season</span></li>
      <li class="season-chip"><span class="s-icon">☀️</span><span class="s-name">Summer</span><span class="s-note">They go deep</span></li>
      <li class="season-chip"><span class="s-icon">🍂</span><span class="s-name">Fall</span><span class="s-note">Second surge</span></li>
      <li class="season-chip"><span class="s-icon">❄️</span><span class="s-name">Winter</span><span class="s-note">Slower, not gone</span></li>
    </ul>
  </header>

  <main>

    <nav class="card" aria-label="Table of contents" style="border-left: 4px solid #059669; padding: 1rem 1.5rem;">
      <p style="font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; color: #6b7280; margin: 0 0 0.65rem;">In This Guide</p>
      <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.9; font-size: 0.9rem;">
        <li><a href="#short-version">The Short Version</a></li>
        <li><a href="#spring">Spring (Feb–May)</a></li>
        <li><a href="#summer">Summer (Jun–Aug)</a></li>
        <li><a href="#fall">Fall (Sep–Nov)</a></li>
        <li><a href="#winter">Winter (Dec–Jan)</a></li>
        <li><a href="#year-round">Year-Round Baseline Rules</a></li>
        <li><a href="#faq">Frequently Asked Questions</a></li>
      </ul>
    </nav>

    <section class="card">
      <h2 id="short-version">The Short Version</h2>
      <p>In most of <a href="/southern-california-gopher-control">California</a>, gophers never fully stop. But there are two hot windows — <strong>spring and fall</strong> — when they go into overdrive. Miss those windows and you're always playing catch-up. Hit them hard during the push and you can actually stay ahead.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="season-grid">

      <article class="season-card season-spring">
        <div class="season-label">Spring</div>
        <h2 id="spring">Feb &ndash; May</h2>
        <p class="season-tagline">Peak Breeding. Maximum Damage.</p>
        <p>This is the big one. Gophers come out of their winter slow-down breeding hard and expanding territory. A single female can drop 2&ndash;3 litters of 5&ndash;6 pups between February and May. New tunnels go in fast, mounds multiply overnight, and root damage hits its annual peak as plants are trying to establish new growth.</p>
        <h3>What Mark Does in Spring</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Start trapping before the first new mound appears — early February if you had activity last fall.</li>
          <li>Walk the yard every morning. <a href="/problems/mound-id">Fresh mounds</a> are your best intel.</li>
          <li>Set traps in pairs in the main runway, not the lateral branches.</li>
          <li>Don't let even one mound sit unchecked for more than 24 hours during this window.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="bagger-tip">
          <strong>Bagger Pro-Tip:</strong> Spring is not the time for repellents. You've got active breeders pushing territory — you need lethal traps or <a href="/methods/poison-bait-stations">bait stations</a> working every day. Castor oil and <a href="/methods/sonic-stakes">sonic stakes</a> are fine as a perimeter hold but they will not stop a breeding surge.
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="season-card season-summer">
        <div class="season-label">Summer</div>
        <h2 id="summer">Jun &ndash; Aug</h2>
        <p class="season-tagline">Underground, But Not Gone.</p>
        <p>Surface activity drops off in the heat. You'll see fewer fresh mounds, and it's easy to think the problem solved itself. It didn't. Gophers go deeper in summer — sometimes 3&ndash;4 feet down — and they keep working your root systems. The lack of surface signs is misleading. Irrigation lines are at especially high risk because gophers follow moisture.</p>
        <h3>What Mark Does in Summer</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Check irrigation lines and drip systems monthly — chewed emitters and wet spots where there shouldn't be any are signs of subsurface activity.</li>
          <li>Maintain any traps you have set — gophers are still moving, just deeper.</li>
          <li>This is a good time to install <a href="/methods/gopher-mesh">gopher mesh</a> under new garden beds before fall planting.</li>
          <li><a href="/traps">Probe</a> areas where turf looks stressed — collapsed tunnels cause dry patches even when you're watering.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="bagger-tip">
          <strong>Bagger Pro-Tip:</strong> If your lawn has a dead patch in summer and irrigation isn't the cause, probe it before you reseed. You're probably standing on a collapsed tunnel. Fill the void first or you'll be reseeding again in three weeks.
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="season-card season-fall">
        <div class="season-label">Fall</div>
        <h2 id="fall">Sep &ndash; Nov</h2>
        <p class="season-tagline">Cache Season. Second Surge.</p>
        <p>Fall brings the second major activity spike of the year. Gophers are caching food — bulbs, roots, tubers — for winter, and they expand their tunnel network aggressively to do it. This is the season they hit vegetable gardens hardest as crops finish and root systems are at their most dense. It's also your second-best trapping window of the year.</p>
        <h3>What Mark Does in Fall</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Get traps back in the ground the moment you see new fall mounds — usually mid-September in <a href="/southern-california-gopher-control">Redlands</a>.</li>
          <li>Pull out any spent summer crops and check the root zones for evidence of gopher feeding.</li>
          <li>If you're planting fall bulbs, put hardware cloth baskets around anything valuable.</li>
          <li>Fall is the best time to install a <a href="/methods/barn-owl-box">barn owl box</a> — owls scout through winter and may nest the following spring.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="bagger-tip">
          <strong>Bagger Pro-Tip:</strong> The gopher that destroys your fall garden is almost always the same one you ignored in August when it went quiet. One gopher in a system can cache enough roots to survive the winter. Don't let them coast.
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="season-card season-winter">
        <div class="season-label">Winter</div>
        <h2 id="winter">Dec &ndash; Jan</h2>
        <p class="season-tagline">Slow Season. Not Off Season.</p>
        <p>In the inland valleys of Southern California, there is no true gopher winter. Temperatures rarely get cold enough to push them fully dormant. Activity drops — you'll see fewer fresh mounds — but tunnels are still being worked, especially after rain when soil loosens. Up in the foothills and in colder climates, gophers slow down more significantly but do not hibernate.</p>
        <h3>What Mark Does in Winter</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Keep a baseline set of traps in any area that had activity in fall — don't fully stand down.</li>
          <li>After the first good rain, walk the yard. Saturated soil collapses old tunnel voids and makes new mounds easy to spot.</li>
          <li>Use the slow season to do infrastructure work: gopher mesh installation, raised bed retrofits, hardware cloth barriers around tree root zones.</li>
          <li>Order replacement traps and gear now so you're stocked before the February push.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="bagger-tip">
          <strong>Bagger Pro-Tip:</strong> Winter prep beats spring panic every time. Two hours of mesh installation in January is worth ten hours of emergency trapping in March. If you know you have gopher pressure, get ahead of it now.
        </div>
      </article>

    </div>

    <section class="card">
      <h2 id="year-round">Year-Round Baseline Rules</h2>
      <p>Regardless of season, these never change:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fresh mound = active gopher.</strong> Set traps within 24 hours, every time.</li>
        <li><strong>No new mounds for 5&ndash;7 days</strong> means the gopher is gone. Anything less is wishful thinking.</li>
        <li><strong>One gopher, one territory.</strong> Eliminate it fully before worrying about neighbors moving in — that comes next.</li>
        <li><strong>Check traps every 12&ndash;24 hours.</strong> A dead gopher left in a trap blocks the tunnel and wastes your set.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="card" style="padding: 1rem 1.5rem;">
      <h2 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Ready to Act?</h2>
      <p style="margin-top: 0;">Head to <a href="/methods" style="color: #047857; font-weight: bold;">The Playbook</a> for step-by-step control methods, or check <a href="/problems" style="color: #047857; font-weight: bold;">Common Problems</a> to identify your specific damage.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>When is the best time to trap gophers?</summary>
          <p>Spring (February–May) is peak season — gophers are breeding hard and expanding territory fast. Fall (September–November) is the second major activity window as they cache food for winter. Hit both surges hard and you can stay ahead of the problem.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Are gophers active year-round?</summary>
          <p>In Southern California, yes — gophers never fully stop. They slow down in winter and go deeper in summer heat, but activity continues throughout the year. In colder climates they reduce significantly in winter but do not hibernate.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Why do I see so many gopher mounds in spring?</summary>
          <p>Spring is peak breeding season. A single female can produce 2–3 litters of 5–6 pups between February and May. New tunnels go in fast and mounds can multiply overnight during this window — which is exactly why it's the most important time to be trapping.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>When is the best time to install gopher mesh or barriers?</summary>
          <p>Winter (December–January) is ideal — gopher activity is at its lowest and you can get infrastructure in place before the spring breeding surge begins in February. Two hours of mesh installation in January is worth ten hours of emergency trapping in March.</p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>
</Layout>

<style>
  /* ── Calendar hero ── */
  .calendar-hero {
    background: #1a3a3a;
    color: #e0f2f1;
    padding: 2.25rem 2rem 2rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .calendar-hero h1 {
    font-size: clamp(1.3rem, 3.5vw, 1.9rem);
    color: #ffffff;
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
    line-height: 1.25;
    max-width: 26ch;
  }

  .cal-sub {
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: #99d6cc;
    margin: 0 0 0.85rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    max-width: 50ch;
  }

  .cal-dateline {
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: #5fa898;
    margin: 0 0 1.6rem;
  }

  .season-strip {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.65rem;
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
  }

  .season-chip {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.08);
    border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.15);
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 0.6rem 1rem;
    min-width: 5.5rem;
    gap: 0.2rem;
  }

  .s-icon { font-size: 1.25rem; line-height: 1; }

  .s-name {
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #e0f2f1;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }

  .s-note {
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    color: #7fc9be;
    text-align: center;
  }

  @media (max-width: 480px) {
    .season-strip { gap: 0.4rem; }
    .season-chip { min-width: 4.5rem; padding: 0.5rem 0.65rem; }
  }

  /* ── Season content grid ── */
  .season-grid {
    display: grid;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(320px, 1fr));
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .season-card {
    background: white;
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    box-shadow: 0 4px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);
    border: 1px solid #e4e4e7;
    border-top: 4px solid #e4e4e7;
  }

  .season-card h2 {
    margin-top: 0.25rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.1rem;
  }

  .season-card h3 {
    color: #18181b;
    font-size: 1rem;
    margin-top: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }

  .season-card ul {
    margin-top: 0;
    padding-left: 1.2rem;
  }

  .season-card li {
    margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }

  .season-label {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    margin-bottom: 0;
    opacity: 0.7;
  }

  .season-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: #52525b;
    margin-top: 0;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }

  .season-spring { border-top-color: #10b981; }
  .season-spring .season-label { color: #047857; }
  .season-spring h2 { color: #047857; }

  .season-summer { border-top-color: #f59e0b; }
  .season-summer .season-label { color: #b45309; }
  .season-summer h2 { color: #b45309; }

  .season-fall { border-top-color: #f97316; }
  .season-fall .season-label { color: #c2410c; }
  .season-fall h2 { color: #c2410c; }

